-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - July 14
-- By Clare Jim
-- Sun Jul 13, 2014 09:57PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 14 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST -- The formal announcement of the findings in the corruption investigation of retired national security chief Zhou Yongkang could come at about the time of an earlier-than-usual annual party meeting late in August. [ID:nNrm1jtX6w]-- Two Hong Kong-funded air pollution studies in the Pearl River Delta region have not been fully disclosed to the public because Guangdong authorities object to releasing "confidential information" in them, the Hong Kong government has admitted. [ID:nNrm8M7gpw] -- China's securities regulator has fallen for digital technology in a big way, with big data - the collection of large and complex data sets - giving its crackdown on "rat traders" a much-needed shot in the arm. [ID:nNrm48y6VK]  THE STANDARD -- Financial Secretary John Tsang Chun-wah joined other officials to call on lawmakers to be courageous and to accept their political responsibility to make difficult decisions in supporting unpopular issues, after only 21 of the 44 funding applications were able to pass the legislative council before the summer recess. (http://bit.ly/1nlBRf2) -- More than 1,000 people protested on Sunday against violence in the Legislative Council. Led by the Hong Kong Federation of Trade Unions, they called for an amendment to legislative council's rules to prevent filibusters and violence during meetings. (http://bit.ly/1myYMbz) -- Sentiment in the Hong Kong home market continues to be hot, with Sino Land <0083.HK> selling nearly 100 units at Park Ivy in Tai Kok Tsui over the weekend and secondary market deals increasing from the previous week. (http://bit.ly/1sR2iyJ)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- The Hong Kong government will announce details about the fourth batch of iBond on Friday and start selling on Monday until the end of July. Analysts expect the yield of the iBond will be 3 to 4 percent in the first year.  -- Hin Sang Hong Company Ltd, which specialises in children healthcare product, plans to raise funds via public offering in Hong Kong in the next few years for expansion in China.HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES -- A-share exchange traded funds (ETFs) listed globally recorded a total inflow of HK$5.5 billion ($709.69 million) last week.  For Chinese newspapers, see...............[PRESS/CN]